Use this file as a reference for each step. Confirm with me before moving onto the next step. 


Refactor strategy
Core rule

Do this as a series of behavior-preserving extraction passes.

That means:

move code
rewire imports/calls
run tests
only then consider cleanup

Not:

“While I’m in here I’ll redesign the whole thing.”

That is how a “quick cleanup” becomes a six-hour fistfight with yourself.

Phase 0 — Safety rails first

Before moving code around, tighten your safety net.

0.1 Run and verify tests locally

Use your real dev environment, not this container goblin cave.

Target suites:

tests/test_storage.py
tests/test_rooms.py
tests/test_app_http.py
0.2 Add a few smoke tests if missing

Before touching canvas.js, backend refactors are safer than frontend ones because the backend already has decent test coverage.

For the frontend, if you don’t already have them, at least keep a manual smoke checklist:

login still works
room create/join still works
draw still works
token create/move/delete still works
assets still upload/place/delete
terrain still renders and repaints
fog still paints/clears
undo/redo still works
snapshots still work
room transfer prompt still works
co-GM / GM restrictions still behave

That checklist becomes your sanity anchor after each split.

0.3 Create one temporary tracking doc

Make a simple REFACTOR_PLAN.md or issue checklist with:

task name
moved from
moved to
tests run
manual checks run

Future-you will thank you instead of trying to murder you.

Phase 1 — Split static/canvas.js without changing architecture

This is the highest-value move in the whole project.

Goal

Keep plain JS. Keep the current app model. Just stop making one file own the whole universe.

Important rule

Do not try to invent a perfect client architecture first.
Just extract by responsibility.

Recommended target structure
static/
  canvas/
    index.js
    state.js
    api.js
    auth.js
    ui.js
    render.js
    network.js
    selection.js
    tokens.js
    assets.js
    terrain.js
    fog.js
    sessions.js
    offline.js
    utils.js

You can tweak names, but the point is to create natural fault lines.

1.1 First extraction pass: low-risk utility modules

These are easiest because they tend to have fewer tentacles.

Move first:
logging helpers
toast helpers
tooltip helpers
formatting helpers
tiny DOM helpers
generic clamp/debounce/throttle/math helpers
pure utility functions
Likely target:
canvas/utils.js
maybe canvas/ui.js
Why first

It reduces file size immediately without destabilizing core game behavior.

1.2 Extract API helpers

Anything like:

fetch wrappers
upload helpers
auth/session HTTP calls
asset library API calls
snapshot API calls
room/session creation/join helpers
Target
canvas/api.js
Benefit

Separates “talk to server” from “what UI does with the answer.”

That’s a very clean win.

1.3 Extract websocket logic

Move:

connect/reconnect logic
socket lifecycle
heartbeat/reconnect handling
message receive dispatch
send wrappers
sync handling / hello flow
Target
canvas/network.js
Important

Do not redesign the protocol yet. Just relocate it.

Why this matters

Right now networking is probably entangled with rendering and UI. Separating it will make bugs much easier to chase.

1.4 Extract terrain and fog into separate modules

These are natural subsystems already.

Move terrain-related code into:
canvas/terrain.js

Likely includes:

terrain texture/material generation
paint mask logic
terrain rendering helpers
terrain state helpers
terrain-related UI actions
Move fog-related code into:
canvas/fog.js

Likely includes:

fog mask storage
fog stroke application
fog render masking
fog-related toggles/tools
Why this is a great split

These systems are complex enough to deserve isolation, and they’re also good examples of feature modules that should not be mixed with login, lobby UI, and pack filtering nonsense.

1.5 Extract asset library logic

Move:

asset panel behavior
asset search/filtering
pack browsing and entitlement displays
placement defaults
saved filters / sets if present
asset usage overrides and presets
Target
canvas/assets.js
Why

Your asset system is already a real product feature. It should stop living in the same pile as generic canvas input plumbing.

1.6 Extract session/lobby/room-move UI logic

Move:

session modal logic
join/move prompts
current session state UI
room switching prompts
pack sharing session logic on the client side
Target
canvas/sessions.js
Why

This is a distinct product workflow. It should not be mixed into raw board interaction code.

1.7 Extract render orchestration

Move:

canvas draw loop
viewport/render orchestration
grid rendering
asset rendering
token rendering
shape/stroke render orchestration
overlay rendering
selection box rendering
Target
canvas/render.js
Important

If render depends heavily on shared globals, that’s okay at first. You are not required to solve state purity on pass one.

Why

Rendering is one of the biggest conceptual domains in the app. Giving it its own home is huge.

1.8 Extract selection + token interaction

Move:

selected IDs/group handling
marquee logic
drag state
token interaction state
maybe context menu selection behavior
Target
canvas/selection.js
possibly canvas/tokens.js
Note

If token-specific code is large enough, give it its own file. If not, let selection own it temporarily.

1.9 Create canvas/state.js

This does not have to be Redux or fancy.

Just centralize shared mutable state.

Example direction:

export const state = {
  room: null,
  me: null,
  ws: null,
  terrain: {},
  fog: {},
  selection: {},
  session: {},
  assets: {},
  ui: {},
};

Even if this is just a shared object, that alone improves clarity because every module now imports the same state rather than inventing neighboring globals like raccoons in adjacent trash cans.

1.10 Leave index.js as the composition root

index.js should become the “wire-up” file:

import modules
initialize app
bind DOM events
bootstrap auth/session state
start render/network lifecycle

That way index.js becomes readable instead of mythological.

Phase 2 — Clean up server/app.py

Once the frontend is less cursed, attack the backend routing shell.

Goal

Keep FastAPI and current routes. Just stop app.py from doing every job personally.

Recommended target structure
server/
  app.py
  auth_helpers.py
  upload_helpers.py
  session_helpers.py
  ws_helpers.py

You can rename these however you want. The idea is extraction by function, not architecture astronautics.

2.1 Extract auth/session helper functions

Move things like:

current-user/session lookup helpers
cookie/session helper logic
membership/ownership checks reused across routes
auth-related utility functions
Target
server/auth_helpers.py
Why

These are cross-cutting concerns and should not stay sprinkled inside route code.

2.2 Extract upload/image/ZIP logic

This one is a very strong candidate.

Move:

extension/MIME helpers
image validation
thumbnail generation
ZIP member sanitization
upload processing helpers
asset import helpers
Target
server/upload_helpers.py
Why

This logic is practical, valuable, and very separable from route declarations.

Also, upload code has a way of quietly becoming a monster if left in the main app file.

2.3 Extract gameplay-session / room-move orchestration helpers

Move:

session summary assembly
room move offer/force helpers
maybe shared pack-related session response composition
Target
server/session_helpers.py
Why

These workflows are product logic, not route plumbing.

2.4 Extract websocket endpoint support helpers

You may or may not need this immediately.

Possible move:

parse/validate ws input helpers
initial hello / room join helper functions
support functions called by ws_room
Target
server/ws_helpers.py
Important

I would not rush to split the websocket endpoint itself into a grand subsystem until after the easy extractions above. Start with helpers first.

Phase 3 — Split server/storage.py by domain

This should happen before the file grows another few hundred lines and begins charging rent.

Goal

Preserve function names and behavior as much as possible, but split the module into domain buckets.

Recommended structure
server/
  storage/
    __init__.py
    models.py
    db.py
    auth.py
    rooms.py
    assets.py
    sessions.py
    snapshots.py

If that feels too ambitious right now, do a flatter version first:

server/
  storage_models.py
  storage_db.py
  storage_auth.py
  storage_rooms.py
  storage_assets.py
  storage_sessions.py

Either is fine.

3.1 Extract model definitions first

Move SQLModel table classes into:

storage_models.py or storage/models.py
Why first

This is the cleanest split and usually lowest risk.

3.2 Extract DB init / engine / session scaffolding

Move:

engine/session creation
init_db()
low-level DB bootstrapping
PRAGMA setup if present
Target
storage_db.py or storage/db.py
3.3 Extract auth persistence

Move:

user creation/fetch
session create/get/delete
auth lookup helpers
Target
storage_auth.py
3.4 Extract room + membership persistence

Move:

room CRUD
room metadata persistence
room membership management
join code creation/resolution if room-related
Target
storage_rooms.py
3.5 Extract assets + packs

Move:

asset rows
asset CRUD
asset listing
private packs
entitlements
pack asset listing
shared pack relationships if tightly coupled
Target
storage_assets.py

This is a very natural boundary in your project.

3.6 Extract gameplay sessions + snapshots

Move:

play sessions
room-sharing/session-sharing relationships
snapshots if they fit better here, or separate them
Target
storage_sessions.py
maybe storage_snapshots.py
3.7 Re-export from a stable top-level interface

Very important for low-risk refactoring.

Your storage/__init__.py or top-level storage.py compatibility shim can re-export current functions so the rest of the code doesn’t immediately need massive import rewrites.

That way you can split internals without detonating every import at once.

Sneaky. Effective. Very human.

Phase 4 — Split server/rooms.py event families

This is not urgent before the frontend split, but it’s the next big backend quality move.

Goal

Keep RoomManager as the orchestration brain while extracting event-application families.

Recommended structure
server/
  room_events/
    __init__.py
    tokens.py
    strokes.py
    shapes.py
    assets.py
    terrain.py
    fog.py

Or flatter if you prefer.

4.1 Keep RoomManager in charge

Do not dissolve the room manager into mist.

Let it remain responsible for:

room lifecycle
connection tracking
presence
history/undo-redo orchestration
autosave
event dispatch
broadcast coordination

That part is good.

4.2 Extract _apply_* families into helpers/modules

Candidates:

_apply_token_event
_apply_stroke_event
_apply_shape_event
_apply_asset_event
_apply_terrain_event
_apply_fog_event
Example shape

Have helpers like:

def apply_token_event(room_state, payload, context): ...

Where context can include:

actor identity
permission helpers
mutation helpers
limits/constants
maybe history hooks where needed
Why

This makes each family easier to reason about and test independently without losing the centralized architecture.

4.3 Consider extracting permission helpers too

If permission logic is starting to spread across event families, consider a dedicated helper module later:

room_permissions.py

But I would only do that once you see actual duplication. Don’t refactor into imaginary future duplication.

Phase 5 — Tighten the event contract

This is the “future bug prevention” phase.

You already have a real client/server event protocol. Right now it’s probably maintained mostly by discipline and tribal knowledge.

Let’s make it less tribal.

Goal

Create a single source of truth for event types and expected payload shapes.

5.1 Centralize event type names

Whether this is in Python, JS, or a tiny shared document, define the canonical event universe.

Even a file like:

docs/protocol.md

or

server/protocol.py

or

static/canvas/protocol.js

would help.

At minimum document:

event type
sender
payload fields
server authority behavior
broadcast behavior
5.2 Validate payload shapes more explicitly

You do not necessarily need full schema-generation wizardry right now.

But if specific event payloads are getting hairy, formalize them more:

token move payloads
asset placement payloads
terrain stroke payloads
fog payloads
room-move/session control payloads

That reduces subtle drift between client and server.

Phase 6 — Documentation pass after refactor

This phase sounds boring and therefore many people skip it and then wonder why the project feels like an abandoned mall.

Do a short architecture refresh when the dust settles.

Add/update:
README.md architecture section
docs/refactor-notes.md or docs/architecture.md
module map for frontend
module map for backend
event protocol summary

This doesn’t need to be fancy. Just truthful.

Recommended execution order

Here’s the order I’d personally use.

Pass A — easiest wins
extract canvas utility helpers
extract canvas API helpers
extract canvas network helpers
extract canvas terrain and fog modules

These give huge readability gains without immediately touching the most delicate interaction code.

Pass B — feature domain splits
extract canvas assets
extract canvas sessions/room-move flow
extract canvas render orchestration
extract canvas selection/token interaction
create canvas/state.js
leave canvas/index.js as bootstrap shell
Pass C — backend cleanup
extract app.py upload helpers
extract app.py auth/session helpers
extract app.py session-room orchestration helpers
Pass D — persistence split
extract storage models
extract DB scaffolding
extract auth persistence
extract rooms/membership persistence
extract assets/packs
extract sessions/snapshots
Pass E — room event cleanup
extract room event families from rooms.py
document event protocol
architecture doc refresh
What not to do during this refactor

Very important.

Do not:
switch frontend frameworks
replace SQLite
redesign the multiplayer model
rewrite the websocket protocol from scratch
mix feature additions into the extraction passes
“clean up everything while you’re here”

Every one of those is a trap disguised as ambition.

Suggested Codex task slices

Here’s how I’d hand this to Codex in manageable chunks.

Task 1

Extract low-risk utility/helper functions from static/canvas.js into static/canvas/utils.js and static/canvas/ui.js, update imports/script loading, preserve behavior, no functional changes.

Task 2

Extract HTTP/API helper functions from static/canvas.js into static/canvas/api.js, preserve all existing behavior and call signatures.

Task 3

Extract websocket lifecycle and message send/receive helpers from static/canvas.js into static/canvas/network.js, preserve reconnect and sync behavior exactly.

Task 4

Extract terrain-related state, rendering helpers, and paint logic from static/canvas.js into static/canvas/terrain.js.

Task 5

Extract fog-related state, rendering helpers, and paint logic from static/canvas.js into static/canvas/fog.js.

Task 6

Extract asset library, pack browser, asset filter, and asset placement helpers from static/canvas.js into static/canvas/assets.js.

Task 7

Extract session/lobby/room-move UI and state helpers from static/canvas.js into static/canvas/sessions.js.

Task 8

Extract rendering orchestration from static/canvas.js into static/canvas/render.js, preserving current draw order and viewport behavior.

Task 9

Create static/canvas/state.js and migrate shared mutable state into it with minimal behavior changes.

Task 10

Extract upload/image/ZIP helper logic from server/app.py into server/upload_helpers.py, preserving all route behavior and tests.

Task 11

Extract auth/session utility helpers from server/app.py into server/auth_helpers.py.

Task 12

Split server/storage.py by domain, starting with model definitions and DB setup, while preserving the public import surface.

Task 13

Extract room event family handlers from server/rooms.py into dedicated helper modules while keeping RoomManager as orchestrator.


